This paper deals with data stream algorithms for estimating the size of maximum matchings in low arboricity graphs. The problem involves designing algorithms that can process large graphs in a single pass with limited memory. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the categories of data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM), which deal with efficient algorithms and combinatorial problems, respectively. The paper also involves analyzing the performance of algorithms in terms of approximation factors and space complexity, which are topics covered in the categories of computational complexity (cs.CC) and graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the category of information theory (cs.IT), which deals with the fundamental limits of data compression and communication.
